<li id="cite_note-88"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-88">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFDoumanis2016" class="citation book cs1">Doumanis, Nicholas, ed. (2016). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Yd8mDAAAQBAJ"><i>The Oxford Handbook of European History, 1914–1945</i></a> (E-book&#160;ed.). Oxford, England: Oxford University Press. pp.&#160;377–378. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780191017759" title="Special:BookSources/9780191017759"><bdi>9780191017759</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2 December</span> 2021</span> &#8211; via Google Books. <q>At first sight, accusations that Hitler and Stalin mirrored each other as they 'conducted wars of annihilation against internal and external enemeis ... of class, race, and nation,' seem plausible. But such a perspective, in reality a recapitulation of the long-discredited totalitarian perspective equating Stalin's Soviet Union with Hitler's National Socialist Germany, is not tenable. It betrays a profound misunderstanding of the distinct natures of the Stalinist and Nazi regimes, which made them mortal enemies. Stalin's primary objective was to forge an autarkic, industrialized, multinational state, under the rubric of 'socialism in one country'. Nationalism and nation-building were on Stalin's agenda, not genocide; nor was it inherent in the construction of a non-capitalist, non-expansionary state—however draconian.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+European+History%2C+1914%E2%80%931945&amp;rft.place=Oxford%2C+England&amp;rft.pages=377-378&amp;rft.edition=E-book&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2016&amp;rft.isbn=9780191017759&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DYd8mDAAAQBAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMass+killings+under+communist+regimes" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEShafir2016-89"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEShafir2016_89-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFShafir2016">Shafir 2016</a>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-90"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-90">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFRadonić2020" class="citation book cs1">Radonić, Ljiljana (2020). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Ks7nDwAAQBAJ"><i>The Holocaust/Genocide Template in Eastern Europe</i></a>. London, England: Routledge. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781000712124" title="Special:BookSources/9781000712124"><bdi>9781000712124</bdi></a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2 December</span> 2021</span> &#8211; via Google Books.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Holocaust%2FGenocide+Template+in+Eastern+Europe&amp;rft.place=London%2C+England&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=2020&amp;rft.isbn=9781000712124&amp;rft.aulast=Radoni%C4%87&amp;rft.aufirst=Ljiljana&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DKs7nDwAAQBAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMass+killings+under+communist+regimes" class="Z3988"></span></span>
